                <h2>How I Got Into The Police</h2>
                <p>When I joined Centrica, I undertook the Duke Of Edinburgh Gold award. One element of the award is to undertake some volunteering.
                    I chose to become a Street Angel in Woking, going on on one Friday and Saturday a month and offer assistance to the people in the
                    town centre that have had to much to drink or are otherwise vulnerable.</p>
                <p>Over the course of a year, I undertook a lot of 'shifts' in the town centre than was expected, as I saw my role as highly useful
                    and important within the town centre. I was given the responsibility of managing a team of 8 Street Angels as we attempted to assist
                    the public and prevent violence. I came into close contact with the police every weekend, even getting to the point that when it was
                    my birthday, I got a card from them!</p>
                <p>However, the level of violence I saw in the Town Centre, and the relatively little amount I could do to try and prevent it that lead
                    me to the police. I applied as a special constable, with the intention of coming back to Woking and 'Cleaning up the streets' so to speak.
                    I was accepted and entered training in August of 2013. After many sacrificed evenins and Weekends, I passed qualification, and out of the
                    initial 12 that made up our intake, I was one of 4 to actually attest in January 2014.</p>
                <p>I stayed on the Woking Neighbourhoods team for a good year before in March 2015, I moved over to Staines to become part of the Response
                    team there, a much more fast paced and skilled role, and I am currently one of only 5 Specials (out of a total 180) who have been cleared to
                    work on response.</p>

