            <h2>From The News...</h2>
            <p><b>A CHRISTMAS NIGHT OUT WITH SURREY POLICE</b></p>
            <P>When I asked Surrey Police if I could head out on a night shift with one of their officers, the force was all too happy to oblige.

                Slightly alarmed by the warning that I could be abandoned at any time during my shift – if the officer were to be called to a particularly serious incident – I layered on the thermals and turned up at Guildford police station at 10pm on Saturday (December 20).

                I picked that date assuming the town centres of our otherwise quiet county would be in turbo pre-Christmas partying mode, and I was not wrong.

                As I clambered into the passenger seat of Inspector Adam Smith’s police car, he informed me that the night before – ‘mad Friday’ – had lived up to its reputation, and that there would be 20 extra police officers on the beat in West Surrey that night, and an additional 24 officers in a police support unit in the county, to deal with the anticipated drama.

                I was given a tour of the police cells at Guildford, in which five people were residing, shortly after 10pm. I caught a glimpse of a pair of women’s boots and other items of clothing lining the doors. By 5.30am, every cell was occupied.

                As Insp Smith and I set off through the streets, all was fairly quiet, but an increased police presence was definitely detectable.</P>
            <p>
                We headed to the notoriously busy Chertsey Street in Woking, but a regular police closure of the road during weekend nights to reduce violence, appeared to be doing its job.

                There was a heavy police presence, with clusters of officers visible.

                With music thumping in the background, special constable Ryan Soper said: “There are lots of people out drinking tonight but there seems to be a positive festive vibe. People seem happy to be out enjoying themselves.”

                By 4.50am however, Woking Police had contacted me on Twitter to say: “It was the calm before the storm...five arrests tonight (fighting and being too drunk).”

                Things were hotting up in the Guildford area too. No sooner had we returned to the car, we were alerted to an alleged common assault incident in Worplesdon Road.

                Police had cordoned off a section of the pavement, where smashed glass was visible.

                Insp Smith spoke to his colleagues to check everything was in hand before the ‘blues-and-twos’ were on and we were haring to another incident, near Popworld nightclub, in Bridge Street.

                In total, we were aware of four alleged assaults recorded during the night, including another outside the Friary Centre in Guildford and a domestic incident in Chilworth. At least two people were knocked unconscious.

                After a tour of the Surrey Police headquarters, at Mount Browne – where I met operators in the force control rooms dealing with calls from the public, and communication with officers themselves, we drove out to Godalming.

                While in the area we were asked to meet a teenager who had set off some type of bangers, and wanted to hand them over.

                A little inebriated, we returned him home.
            </p>
