            <p>
                By the end of my shift, at 4.30am, there were 13 people in custody in Guildford, along with those in the ‘hold’.

                Those in custody were being investigated for alleged incidents including attempted murder, assault, taking without owners consent, affray, grievous bodily harm, actual bodily harm, being drunk and disorderly, and drink-driving.

                Many of them would be held well into the next day.

                Insp Smith said in his experience, New Year’s Eve was the night most drink-related incidents occur.

                “People have been partying hard for a long time, and perhaps their tolerance is reducing, and there is a psychology behind it too,” he said. “People tend to act like there is no tomorrow.

                “The trick for us, like tonight, is to take action early in the evening and use our dispersal powers to clear the area.

                “Licensed premises are increasingly helping too, and have started clearing their own areas after close.”

                Having been with the force almost all his working life, Insp Smith said there were still days when his job "gets to him".

                Being on the scene shortly after the A3 coach crash, which killed three people in September 2012, stays with him, and more recently, he was moved by the death of 11-year-old Pravini Angel Parathisan, who was killed when the car she was travelling in came off the road and hit a tree on December 8.

                “I had to call my wife and check the girls were alright,” he said. “We are all human and some of the things we deal with are truly awful.

                “My role is to bring ordered chaos from absolute chaos. I usually arrive after an incident has happened, but I can help the family. I can help by helping them get the answers they need.”
            </p>
